iables used to calculate it.\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n10,FOCUS GROUP,MARKET RESEARCH,Focus group is related to market research. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n11,MARKET RESEARCH,FOCUS GROUP,Market research is related to focus group. They are both research techniques to deal with uncertainty.\n\nOutput:\n{{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter 8: Risk and Uncertainty\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter 8 covers the following Learning Outcomes. C. Decision-Making Techniques 6. Dealing with risk and uncertainty in decision making a) Suggest research techniques to reduce uncertainty (e.g. focus groups, market research). b) Explain the use of simulation, expected values and sensitivity. c) Apply expected values and sensitivity to decision-making problems. d) Apply the techniques of maximax, maximin and minimax regret to decision-making problems, including the production of profit tables. e) Interpret a decision tree and use it to solve a multi-stage decision problem. f) Calculate the value of perfect and imperfect information. \",\n    \"rating\": 7.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the fundamental importance of bookkeeping in accounting.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Focus groups and market research are important research techniques to reduce uncertainty\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Companies often use focus groups and/or market research to deal with uncertainty. Focus groups are used to reduce uncertainty about new products by gathering opinions from a group of people in an interactive environment. Participants are chosen at random and may be observed by marketing professionals. Market Research involves the systematic gathering and analyzing of data about consumers, competitors, and market conditions to inform business decisions. It provides insights into market trends, customer preferences, and competitive dynamics. This process can be based on primary or secondary data and is used to assess the potential success of new product launches. By understanding consumers' needs and preferences, companies can make informed decisions about product development and marketing strategies. Market Research serves as an external source of valuable information that helps businesses navigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n947,\"\"\"SALES VOLUME VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Sales Volume Variance\"\" is a financial metric that measures the difference between the actual quantity of units sold and the budgeted quantity expected to be sold, valued at the standard contribution per unit. It can be calculated using several formulas, including:\n\n1. Sales volume variance = (Actual quantity sold - Budgeted quantity sold) x Standard selling price\n2. Sales volume variance = (Actual sales - Budgeted sales) * Standard profit per unit\n3. Sales volume variance = (Actual sales quantity - Budgeted sales quantity) * Standard contribution per unit\n4. Sales volume variance = (Actual sales volume - Budget sales volume) * Standard contribution\n\nThis variance indicates whether more or fewer units were sold than expected and shows the effect on profit of selling more or less than the budgeted quantity. Additionally, sales volume variance can be analyzed into a market size (planning) variance and a market share (operational) variance.\",16\n948,\"\"\"SALES PRICE VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Sales Price Variance\"\" is a financial metric used to measure the impact on profit due to differences between the actual selling price and the standard selling price. It is calculated by comparing the actual price to the standard price, multiplied by the actual volume sold. The formula for sales price variance is (Actual Selling Price - Standard Selling Price) * Actual Quantity Sold. This variance highlights the effect on profit when products are sold at prices higher or lower than the standard price.\",10\n1010,\"\"\"PLANNING VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Planning variance\"\" arises when an original budget is revised with the benefit of hindsight, i.e., after the fact. It can relate to any element of the standard product specification or to sales/production volumes. Planning variance is the difference between the original standard cost and the revised standard cost of actual output. In this case, it is $390,400 (A). Additionally, planning variance refers to the difference between the original budgeted performance and the revised budgeted performance, which can be attributed to changes in external factors or inaccurate initial forecasts.\",9\n1031,\"\"\"MARKET SHARE VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Market share variance (sales volume operational variance) measures the difference between the actual sales volume and the revised budgeted sales volume, based on the actual market size. It helps in understanding the impact of market share changes on sales volume. The formula for calculating market share variance is: (Actual sales quantity - Revised budgeted quantity) * Standard contribution/profit per unit. Alternatively, it can also be expressed as (Actual sales volume - revised sales volume) * standard contribution. Essentially, market share variance is the difference between the actual sales and the budgeted market share of the actual market. For instance, in a quiz scenario involving Riley Co, the market share variance would be calculated by considering the actual market size and sales achieved compared to the budgeted market share and sales.\"\"\",7\n1030,\"\"\"MARKET SIZE VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Market size variance\"\" is a financial metric used to measure the difference between actual and expected market performance. It can be calculated using several formulas. One method is: (Actual market size * Budgeted market share - Budgeted sales quantity) * Standard contribution/profit per unit. Another approach is: (Revised sales volume - Budget sales volume) * Standard contribution. A third formula is: (Original budget quantity - Revised standard quantity) * Standard contribution/profit per unit. Each of these methods provides a way to assess the impact of market size changes on profitability.\",5\n1011,\"\"\"OPERATIONAL VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Operational variance\"\" arises when actual performance differs from a revised standard. It is calculated similarly to traditional variances but uses a revised standard. This variance refers to the difference between the actual performance and the expected performance, which can be attributed to factors within the control of the management, such as efficiency and effectiveness in operations.\",5\n938,\"\"\"SALES VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"Sales variances\"\" are calculated to determine the difference between actual sales and budgeted sales. These variances can be broken down into several components, including sales volume variance, sales price variance, market size variance, and market share variance. The process involves using a flexed budget approach to analyze the variances, given the budgeted and actual sales data. This comprehensive analysis helps in understanding the underlying factors contributing to the differences in sales performance.\",5\n1821,\"\"\"PURCHASING MANAGER PERFORMANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"The performance of the purchasing manager is evaluated based on variances such as material price variance and material usage variance, and their impact on overall costs and quality.\"\"\",4\n2227,\"\"\"SALES PERFORMANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Sales performance analysis involves evaluating the effectiveness of sales strategies and decisions, such as pricing and market positioning, in achieving sales targets.\"\"\",4\n1501,\"\"\"MATERIAL USAGE VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Material usage variance\"\" is calculated as the difference between the actual quantity of materials used and the standard quantity allowed or expected to be used, multiplied by the standard cost per unit or per kilogram. This variance measures the effect of the actual quantity of materials used differing from the standard quantity, evaluated using the standard price per unit. For example, a material usage variance might be given as $100A.\",8\n1032,\"\"\"SALES PLANNING AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES QUIZ\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the traditional sales volume variance, market size variance, and market share variance for Acme based on given sales data.\"\"\",3\n1051,\"\"\"STANDARD COSTING AND VARIANCE ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"Standard costing and variance analysis aim to improve operational efficiency by comparing actual performance to standard performance and analyzing variances.\"\"\",2\n1033,\"\"\"ADVANTAGES AND DISADVANTAGES OF VARIANCE ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"Advantages include distinguishing between variances caused by planning or operating factors and providing feedback control. Disadvantages are not provided in the text.\"\"\",1\n2212,\"\"\"NET PROFIT BASIS\"\"\",\"\"\"Net profit basis for sales volume variance is calculated as the difference between actual and budgeted sales units multiplied by the profit per unit.\"\"\",1\n2239,\"\"\"QUANTITY VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Quantity variance = (Actual quantity - Budgeted quantity) x Standard contribution per unit\"\"\",1\n2213,\"\"\"MATERIAL AND LABOUR VARIANCE ANALYSIS FOR PAN-OCEAN CHEMICALS\"\"\",\"\"\"Pan-Ocean Chemicals produces Synthon using three types of materials and labor. The case involves calculating material mix, yield, and usage variances, as well as labor rate and efficiency variances, based on standard and actual costs and quantities.\"\"\",5\n1826,\"\"\"EVALUATING THE IMPACT OF ORGANIC INGREDIENT USAGE ON PRODUCTION AND SALES PERFORMANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Crumbly Cakes, a company that makes cakes sold directly to the public, evaluated the impact of using only organic ingredients on production and sales performance. The new production manager, a celebrity chef, argued that organic ingredients would improve flavor and health benefits, potentially increasing demand and allowing for a price increase. The company operates a responsibility-based standard costing system, and the variance reports for February and March showed mixed results, with the production manager facing adverse variances and the sales manager seeing favorable variances.\"\"\",4\n1502,\"\"\"MATERIAL MIX VARIANCE\"\"\",\"Material mix variance is calculated as the difference between the actual quantity at standard mix and the actual quantity at actual mix, multiplied by the standard cost per unit. It measures the effect of the actual mix of materials used differing from the standard mix, evaluated using the standard price per unit. The formula for material mix variance is (Actual mix - Standard mix) * Standard price. For instance, in a specific calculation, the material mix variance was determined to be $800A.\",5\n1503,\"\"\"MATERIAL YIELD VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Material yield variance\"\" is a metric used to measure the efficiency of material usage in production. It is calculated by comparing the actual yield to the standard yield, with the difference then multiplied by the standard cost per unit. The formula for material yield variance is (Actual yield - Standard yield) * Standard cost per unit. This variance highlights the effect of the actual yield differing from the expected yield based on the standard input, and it is evaluated using the standard price per unit. For instance, a material yield variance can be calculated as $700F, indicating a favorable variance.\",5\n1824,\"\"\"SALES VOLUME CONTRIBUTION VARIANCE\"\"\",\"The \"\"SALES VOLUME CONTRIBUTION VARIANCE\"\" is calculated by comparing the actual volume to the budgeted volume, then multiplying the difference by the standard contribution per unit. The formula for this calculation is (Actual volume - Budget volume) * Standard contribution. This variance helps in assessing the impact of sales volume differences on the overall contribution margin by taking into account the standard contribution per unit.\",3\n1860,\"\"\"STANDARD COST OPERATING STATEMENT\"\"\",\"\"\"The standard cost operating statement contains material price and usage variances, labour rate and efficiency variances, and overhead expenditure and efficiency variances for the previous month.\"\"\",4\n1837,\"\"\"SALES PERFORMANCE VARIANCE ANALYSIS FOR VALET CO AMID ECONOMIC CHALLENGES\"\"\",\"\"\"Valet Co, a car valeting company in Strappia, faced economic challenges due to a global financial crisis. Despite increased petrol and food prices and a decrease in disposable household income, Valet Co's actual figures for full and mini valets exceeded budgeted figures. The case involves analyzing the company's sales performance variance, considering factors like increased car repair business and the closure of a competitor.\"\"\",2\n1012,\"\"\"PLANNING COST VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"Planning cost variances are calculated by analyzing traditional variances into planning and operational variances. This approach is preferred for performance management exams.\"\"\",2\n2214,\"\"\"REVISED STANDARD COST OF ACTUAL OUTPUT\"\"\",\"\"\"Revised standard cost of actual output (122,000 units * 1.4 hours * $13 per hour) = $2,220,400\"\"\",2\n1009,\"\"\"TRADITIONAL VARIANCE ANALYSIS\"\"\",\"\"\"Traditional variance analysis compares actual performance versus expected performance. Management should consider revising standards if the actual environment differs from what was anticipated or if hindsight shows an unrealistic standard was used.\"\"\",2\n2218,\"\"\"LABOUR PRICE PLANNING VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour price planning variance is calculated as the difference between the actual output at revised standard time per unit at original standard rate and the actual output at revised standard time per unit at revised standard rate. In this case, it is $170,800 (A).\"\"\",1\n2217,\"\"\"LABOUR USAGE PLANNING VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Labour usage planning variance is calculated as the difference between the actual output at original standard time per unit and the actual output at revised standard time per unit, both multiplied by the original standard rate. In this case, it is $219,600 (A).\"\"\",1\n1499,\"\"\"TOTAL MATERIAL COST VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Total material cost variance is calculated as the sum of the material price variance and the material usage variance. In this case, it is $4,900A.\"\"\",2\n2219,\"\"\"PRINCIPLES OF REVISING STANDARDS\"\"\",\"\"\"Principles of revising standards involve ensuring that managers are judged only on factors they can control. Standards should be revised for uncontrollable factors before variance analysis is performed to reflect accurate performance. Revisions should be authorized by a senior, independent body to ensure fairness.\"\"\",1\n1831,\"\"\"MATERIAL PRICE VARIANCES\"\"\",\"\"\"Material price variance is calculated as (Actual Price - Standard Price) * Actual Quantity. It measures the difference between the actual cost of materials and the standard cost. Material price variances are calculated by comparing the actual price per kilogram of ingredients to the standard price per kilogram, multiplied by the actual quantity used. The formula is (AP - SP) * AQ.\"\"\",3\n1296,\"\"\"RETURN ON CAPITAL EMPLOYED\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves calculating the return on capital employed (ROCE) for a company using given ratios such as gross profit margin, operating profit margin, gearing, and asset turnover.\"\"\",1\n1846,\"\"\"SAFE SOAP CO\"\"\",\"\"\"The Safe Soap Co makes a contribution of $3.6 on each batch of soap sold. The budgeted sales of 120,000 batches were based on achieving a market share of 10%. The actual sales of the total market in September were 1.4 million units. The market share variance for the month of September was calculated to be $14,400 adverse.\"\"\",1\n1500,\"\"\"MATERIAL PRICE VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Material price variance is the difference between the actual cost of materials and the standard cost, given as $4,800A.\"\"\",2\n2215,\"\"\"OPERATING VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Operating variance is the difference between the revised standard cost and the actual cost. In this case, it is $222,040 (F).\"\"\",3\n1861,\"\"\"PRODUCTION MANAGER\"\"\",\"\"\"The production manager at Kappa Co is responsible for the efficiency of the Omega production process and receives a standard cost operating statement at the end of each month.\"\"\",1\n2216,\"\"\"ACTUAL LABOUR COST\"\"\",\"\"\"Actual labour cost = $1,998,360\"\"\",1\n2220,\"\"\"FACTORS FOR VARIANCE INVESTIGATION\"\"\",\"\"\"Factors to consider in deciding whether a variance should be investigated include the size of the variance, whether it is adverse or favorable, cost versus benefits of investigation, historic pattern of variances, and the reliability and quality of data.\"\"\",1\n1058,\"\"\"OPERATIONAL USAGE (EFFICIENCY) VARIANCE\"\"\",,1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n875,\"\"\"SALES VOLUME VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"SALES PRICE VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Both are types of sales variances, with volume variance focusing on quantity sold and price variance focusing on selling price.\"\"\",26\n887,\"\"\"SALES VOLUME VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"PLANNING VARIANCE\"\"\",\"\"\"Planning variance includes Sales volume variance as it mea